Over past 6 moths or so I was fortunate to explore a few different fidelities of coding with agents and some sort of aesthetics have emerged for me:

- tasks = good. in fact so good that it's worth building the whole flow around them
- subagents are helping a lot when you run a lot of agents at the same time
- while access to full codebase is less critical, in order to be able to maintain quality, you still gotta review the diffs. For multi-agentic flow it is different tho: you want to review changes as PRs, not as diffs within one task
- prompting is pain in the ass and should be delegated to LLMs
- different LLMs and agents = good. I still use GPT-5.2 for planning and code review  and CC or even something more exotic for busywork

As a result flow for me now as following: 
- come up with feature or bug and write initial prompt 
- this adds a 'task' which contains of generated by LLM plan
- you review and edit plan 
- on approval you can assign this plan to agent who will work on code
- when agent done you can run verification agent and address issues if any
- generate commit message and merge 
- task gets archived to be referenced in future

this flow lets you work on multiple features at the same time since agents are not having clashing changes and you merge frequent and without issues (mostly)

anybody uses something similar?
